<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-07T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-07T15:00:00-05:00" n="566" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d566">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94112/32: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-07T16:00:00-04:00">September 7, 1937—4
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your September 6, 6 p.m. The Japanese Government on September 5 announced
                            that Tsingtao was excluded from the area covered by the Japanese
                            blockade of Chinese shipping. Haichow however is not mentioned. Although
                            this Government has in no wise recognized the validity of such a
                            blockade, the Department can, of course, give no assurances that
                            shipments of American cargo from Tsingtao on Chinese vessels will not be
                            seized by the Japanese.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
